    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically just someone guarding the money so nobody gets cheated? who actually manages the account, like is it the lawyer or a bank?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's more than just guarding the money; it's about guaranteeing the *completion* of the deal, which is a much more complex undertaking than just watching a pile of cash. While a bank *could* technically hold funds, in the real estate world, the management of the escrow account is almost always handled by a licensed real estate lawyer or a specialized title company. These professionals are the ones who have the legal authority and the fiduciary duty to manage those funds according to the terms of the purchase agreement. They act as the gatekeepers, ensuring that the transfer of funds and the transfer of ownership happen simultaneously and correctly.",
